8. flush()
The flush() method in Python is used to quickly send data from the computer's temporary storage, known as a buffer, to a file or the screen. 
Normally, when you write something in Python, it doesn't get saved or shown right away. It stays in a buffer for a short time to make things faster.

import time
with open("gfg.txt", "w") as file:
    file.write("First line\n") 
    file.flush() # immediately write to disk
    print("First line written and flushed.")
    time.sleep(2)           
    file.write("Second line\n")








